{
  "answer": "**Āśauca** (also *aśauca* or ritual impurity, especially *sūtaka* from birth or *mṛtyuśauca* from death) is a key concept in several Dharmaśāstra texts in the corpus, particularly regarding periods of impurity for *sapiṇḍas* (shared blood relatives), rules for purification, restrictions on rites like study or eating during impurity, and variations by *varṇa* (caste). It is not found verbatim as \"asauca\" in English translations but is discussed extensively under terms like \"impurity,\" \"*sūtaka*,\" \"*āśauca*,\" \"*sūtyāśauca*,\" and \"*mṛtāśauca*.\" The corpus does not cover every nuance (e.g., no Jain or Buddhist texts on this), but here are the main works:\n\n### Primary Discussions\n- **Aṅgirasa Smṛti** (Chapter 1): Extensive treatment, including impurity during *śrāddha* rites, *sūtyāśauca* (birth impurity) and *mṛtāśauca* (death impurity), continuous impurity in large families, durations like 10/3/1 days, and bathing as purification.[^1]\n- **Manusmṛti**:\n  - Chapter 5: Prohibits food from houses in \"impurity from childbirth\" or before \"the ten days of impurity\" (post-death) are over.[^2]\n  - Chapter 6: Details *sūtaka* periods (e.g., 10 days for *sapiṇḍas* from death/birth, shorter for distant kin or teachers), overlapping impurities, and exemptions (e.g., no impurity for childless elderly abandoned in forest).[^3]\n- **Viṣṇu Smṛti** (Chapter 22): A full chapter on *āśauca* durations by *varṇa* (10 days for Brāhmaṇa *sapiṇḍas*, up to 1 month for Śūdra; shorter for lower *varṇa* kin), overlapping cases, exemptions (e.g., no impurity for suicides, those killed in battle), and purifications (e.g., Gāyatrī recitation, bathing).[^4]\n- **Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (Chapter 1): Brief mentions in contexts like forbidden foods and rites during impurity.[^5]\n\n### Related Mentions\nShorter references appear in **Brhaspati Smṛti** (on shared impurity in inheritance)[^6] and **Parāśara Smṛti** (Chapter 5, on funeral rites during impurity). No discussions in non-Indic works like *Elene* or *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana* (their \"impurity\" is metaphorical).\n\nThese Smṛtis (ancient Dharmaśāstras) form the core coverage; the topic is absent from the 37 works' other genres/eras (e.g., no Greek, Medieval European, or early English texts).\n\n[^1]: Aṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1/paragraph p-bf0738](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-bf0738), [p-117a88](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-117a88), etc.\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 5/paras p-7851cc & p-15103f](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-7851cc).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 6](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/).\n[^4]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 22](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/22/translation/).\n[^5]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, [Chapter 1](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/).\n[^6]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, [Chapter 1/p-c29540](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c29540).",
